# Reply layout (scaffold)

- **Start every reply** with exactly one **`<b>…</b>`** block (**four** lines inside it), then a blank line, then the body of your answer. **This block shape is non-negotiable** — do not omit, reorder, or rename these keys.

```html
<b>rules: scaffold[, other-package-dir …]
skills: null
path: scaffold 2.1ms - scrollsmatrix 1.9ms
user prompt: [one-line restatement of what they asked]</b>
```

- **`rules:`** — Comma-separated **workspace folder names** whose `.cursor/rules` apply (always include **`scaffold`** when this file is in play; add others when their rules clearly apply).
- **`skills:`** — If you **read or followed** an Agent Skill this turn: **`skill-name`** (or filename) and **repo-relative dir** (e.g. `scaffold/.cursor/skills/foo`). If you used **no** skills this turn, the line must be exactly **`skills: null`** (no second column, no em dash).
- **`path:`** (inside `<b>`) — **Directory route only** — which **package roots** you spent wall time in to get context (reads, search, terminals under that cwd). **Do not** list individual filenames here; dirs + durations only. One segment per distinct top-level package dir; **merge** repeat visits into **one cumulative wall-time** per dir.
  - **Duration (`msrules` — same everywhere):** track **real wall ms** internally, then print:
    - **Wall under 10000 ms:** **`(ms / 1000).toFixed(1)` + `ms`**. Examples: 2100 ms → **`2.1ms`**; 500 ms → **`0.5ms`**. Fleet display scale, not SI ms.
    - **Wall 10000 ms and above:** **`(ms / 10000).toFixed(1)` + `kms`** (**`1.0kms`** = 10000 ms wall). Examples: 33000 ms → **`3.3kms`**.
  - Separate segments with **` - `**. Order by **chronology of first use** of that dir, or if unclear, by **decreasing** wall time.

- **`user prompt:`** — One line: what you understood them to want.

- **Timing honesty:** Use **measured** elapsed time when the tool or terminal output gives it; otherwise give a **good-faith estimate** (still use **`msrules`** above).

- **After `</b>`:** Answer directly. **Do not** prefix with **`Check:`**, **`Summary:`**, **`Same rules (content):`**, etc. Only expand on rules/skills/path if the user asked for an audit.

- **Trivial** follow-ups (“yes”, “ok”): same **four-line** `<b>` block; if no repo dirs were used for context, use **`path: (none) —`**. **`skills:`** still **`null`** when no skills were read.

## `cpath:` after your answer (non-negotiable)

- **After the full substantive reply** (all paragraphs, code, lists), the **very last line** of the message must be a **second** HTML block, **only** this shape (own line):

`<b>cpath: scaffold/rules 0.1ms - scrollsmatrix/rules 0.1ms</b>`

- **Purpose:** **`path:`** = package dirs you roamed. **`cpath:`** = **what kinds of guidance** you used (rules, agents, or a **slow** rules file), with **`msrules`** times — **never** print **`.cursor`** in `cpath` (omit that path segment from the label).

- **Segment labels (no `.cursor` ever):**
  - **`{package}/rules`** — wall time for **`.cursor/rules`** in that package **when every individual `.mdc` you read there was under 1000 ms** wall. **Merge** those reads into **one cumulative** time per `{package}/rules`.
  - **`{package}/rules/<filename>.mdc`** — use **only** when **that one file’s** guiding wall time is **greater than 1000 ms** (strictly over one second). Then that file gets its **own** segment with the **real filename**; do **not** also duplicate that time under a bare `{package}/rules` bucket for the same file.
  - **`{package}/agents`** — wall time for that package’s **`AGENTS.md`** when its guiding wall time is **≤ 1000 ms**.
  - **`{package}/AGENTS.md`** — use **only** when reading **`AGENTS.md`** in that package took **> 1000 ms** wall (filename visible because it was slow).

- **Durations:** same **`msrules`** as **`path:`** (`N.Nms` under 10 s wall per segment, **`kms`** from 10 s wall).

- **Order:** chronological **first use** of each segment, or if unclear, descending time.

- **If nothing** guided the reply: **`<b>cpath: null</b>`** (exactly).
